{"title_page": "Marasmarcha oxydactylus", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of plume moth}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| taxon = Marasmarcha oxydactylus\n| authority = ([[Otto Staudinger|Staudinger]], 1859)<ref>[http://www.faunaeur.org/full_results.php?id=438147 Fauna Europaea]</ref>\n| synonyms =\n*''Pterophorus oxydactylus'' <small>Staudinger, 1859</small>\n*''Marasmarcha wullschlegeli'' <small>M\u00fcller-Rutz, 1914</small>\n}}\n'''''Marasmarcha oxydactylus''''' is a [[moth]] of the family [[Pterophoridae]]. It is found in [[Spain]], [[Portugal]], [[Switzerland]], [[Austria]] [[France]] and [[Italy]]. In Europe, the northern limit of the range are the Austrian [[Alps]]. It is also found in [[North Africa]].<ref>[https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/455/45511220011.pdf Faunistische Daten zur Verbreitung der Pterophoridae auf der Iberischen Halbinsel (Lepidoptera: Pterophoridae)]</ref>\n\nThe [[wingspan]] is 18\u201323&nbsp;mm.<ref>[http://www.lepiforum.de/cgi-bin/lepiwiki.pl?Marasmarcha_Oxydactylus lepiforum.de]</ref>\n\nThe larvae feed on ''[[Ononis rotundifolia]]''.<ref>[http://www.nic.funet.fi/pub/sci/bio/life/insecta/lepidoptera/ditrysia/pterophoroidea/pterophoridae/pterophorinae/marasmarcha/index.html Marasmarcha at funet]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q6754893}}\n\n[[Category:Moths described in 1859]]\n[[Category:Exelastini]]\n[[Category:Moths of Europe]]\n\n\n{{Exelastini-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of plume moth}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| taxon = Marasmarcha oxydactylus\n| authority = ([[Otto Staudinger|Staudinger]], 1859)<ref>[http://www.faunaeur.org/full_results.php?id=438147 Fauna Europaea]</ref>\n| synonyms =\n*''Pterophorus oxydactylus'' <small>Staudinger, 1859</small>\n*''Marasmarcha wullschlegeli'' <small>M\u00fcller-Rutz, 1914</small>\n}}\n'''''Marasmarcha oxydactylus''''' is a [[moth]] of the family [[Pterophoridae]]. It is found in [[Spain]], [[Portugal]], [[Switzerland]], [[Austria]] [[France]] and [[Italy]]. In Europe, the northern limit of the range are the Austrian [[Alps]]. It is also found in [[North Africa]].<ref>[http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/pdf/455/45511220011.pdf Faunistische Daten zur Verbreitung der Pterophoridae auf der Iberischen Halbinsel (Lepidoptera: Pterophoridae)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120923051424/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/pdf/455/45511220011.pdf |date=2012-09-23 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[wingspan]] is 18\u201323&nbsp;mm.<ref>[http://www.lepiforum.de/cgi-bin/lepiwiki.pl?Marasmarcha_Oxydactylus lepiforum.de]</ref>\n\nThe larvae feed on ''[[Ononis rotundifolia]]''.<ref>[http://www.nic.funet.fi/pub/sci/bio/life/insecta/lepidoptera/ditrysia/pterophoroidea/pterophoridae/pterophorinae/marasmarcha/index.html Marasmarcha at funet]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q6754893}}\n\n[[Category:Moths described in 1859]]\n[[Category:Exelastini]]\n[[Category:Moths of Europe]]\n\n\n{{Exelastini-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Logan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:bad link repair, replaced: http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/ \u2192 https://www.redalyc.org/ (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marasmarcha_oxydactylus"}
{"title_page": "Ayesha Verrall", "text_new": "{{short description|Physician and infectious diseases researcher}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ayesha Verrall\n| image              = \n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| other_names        = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place        = [[Invercargill]]\n| nationality        = [[New Zealand]]\n| education          = [[University of Otago]]\n| occupation         = Infectious diseases physician and researcher\n| years_active       = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Ayesha Jennifer Verrall''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|FRACP}} is a [[New Zealand]] [[Infectious disease (medical specialty)|infectious diseases]] physician and researcher with expertise in [[tuberculosis]] and [[international health]]. She is also a senior lecturer at the [[University of Otago]], [[Wellington]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.otago.ac.nz/healthsciences/expertise/Profile/index.html?id=1377|title=Dr Ayesha Verrall {{!}} Division of Health Sciences|last=|first=|date=|website=otago.ac.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019-20 coronavirus epidemic]], she provided the New Zealand [[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]] with an independent review and recommendations for its [[contact tracing]] approach to COVID-19 cases.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.health.govt.nz/publication/rapid-audit-contact-tracing-covid-19-new-zealand|title=Rapid Audit of Contact Tracing for COVID-19 in New Zealand|last=Verrall|first=Ayesha|date=2020-04-20|website=|publisher=[[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>  \n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nVerrall was born in [[Invercargill]] and raised in [[Te Anau]]. Her mother is from the [[Maldives]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Gibb|first=John|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/natural-immunity-solving-tb-mystery|title=Natural immunity: solving a Tb mystery|date=2014-11-08|work=Otago Daily Times|access-date=2020-04-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nVerrall trained in medicine at the [[University of Otago Dunedin School of Medicine]], where she obtained her [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery (MBChB)]] in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.otago.ac.nz/careers/otago067425.html|title=Ayesha Verrall|last=|first=|date=|website=Career Development Centre {{!}} otago.ac.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>  She was president of the [[Otago University Students' Association]] in 2001<ref name=\":2\" /> and in 2003 also led a group of medical students to form the New Zealand Medical Student Journal (NSMJ).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nzmsj.com/history.html|title=History|website=New Zealand Medical Student Journal|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> During the next decade, Verrall trained in [[tropical medicine]], [[bioethics]] and [[international health]] in Singapore, USA and Peru.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/graduate-funded-tb-study|title=Graduate funded for Tb study|last=Gibb|first=John|date=2012-11-28|website=Otago Daily Times Online News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Verrall earned a Diploma in Tropical Medicine and Hygiene from the [[Instituto Conmemorativo Gorgas de Estudios de la Salud|Gorgas Institute]] in [[Lima|Lima, Peru]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.otago.ac.nz/internationalhealth/otago661680.html|title=Dr Ayesha Verrall {{!}} Centre for International Health|last=|first=|date=|website=otago.ac.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Verrall completed her PhD in [[Epidemiology of tuberculosis|tuberculosis epidemiology]] at the University of Otago, in collaboration with [[Padjadjaran University]] in [[Indonesia]] and [[Radboud University Nijmegen]] in the [[Netherlands]]. Her research investigated the early clearance immune response of the [[Mycobacterium tuberculosis]] infection among Indonesian people who were highly exposed to the bacteria, yet remained uninfected.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite thesis|title=Innate Factors in Early Clearance of Mycobacterium tuberculosis|url=https://ourarchive.otago.ac.nz/handle/10523/7999|publisher=University of Otago|date=2018|degree=Thesis|language=en|first=Ayesha Jennifer|last=Verrall}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nVerrall is a senior lecturer at [[University of Otago]] in the Department of Pathology and Molecular Medicine. She teaches microbiology to medical students and researches tuberculosis epidemiology and immunology.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nVerrall is also an infectious diseases physician at the [[Capital and Coast District Health Board]] in Wellington and became an elected member of its board in 2019 where she currently serves as deputy board chair. She also provides advise to the government on vaccines, outbreaks and disease prevention. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ccdhb.org.nz/about-us/our-board/|title=CCDHB Board Members|last=|first=|date=|website=ccdhb.org.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> During the [[2019\u20132020 New Zealand measles outbreak]], she advocated for a more strategic approach for allocating more government funding and resources towards increasing vaccination rates for measles, as well as preventing future outbreaks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/112695463/concerted-effort-needed-to-increase-measles-vaccinations-and-prevent-further-outbreaks--expert|title=Concerted effort needed to increase measles vaccinations and prevent further outbreaks - expert|last=Macandrew|first=Ruby|date=2019-05-14|website=Stuff|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, during the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Verrall called for the the New Zealand Government to urgently improve their data on community spread of the coronavirus disease [[COVID-19]] through expanding the testing criteria beyond sick people, increasing laboratory testing and contact tracing capabilities. At the time, the Ministry of Health (MoH) was tracing the contacts of 50 cases per day; Verrall called for up to a 1000 people's contacts to be traced every day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/03/coronavirus-doctors-warn-of-blind-spot-in-government-s-covid-19-response-plan.html|title=Coronavirus: Doctors warn of blind spot in Government's COVID-19 response plan|work=Newshub|access-date=2020-04-21|language=en}}</ref>  \n\nSubsequently, Verrall was commissioned by the MoH to provide an independent audit of its contact tracing programme.<ref name=\":1\" /> The report was initially submitted to the MoH in early April and made publicly available on 20 April to allow the government time to respond and implement some of the recommendations.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Davison|first=Isaac|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12325778|title=Covid 19 coronavirus: Scientists sound level 3, contact tracing alarm bells|date=2020-04-18|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2020-04-21|url-status=live|last2=Johnston|first2=Kirsty|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/04/coronavirus-dr-bloomfield-announces-advancements-in-contact-tracing.html|title=Coronavirus: Dr Bloomfield announces advancements in contact tracing|date=|work=Newshub|access-date=2020-04-22|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> Verrall's audit identified shortcomings in the health sector's approach, which was \"understaffed and lacked cohesion\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/04/contact-tracing-audit-exposes-significant-shortcomings-in-health-system.html|title=Contact tracing audit exposes significant shortcomings in health system|date=|work=Newshub|access-date=2020-04-22|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> The country's 12 \"devolved\" public health units (PHUs) made it difficult to coordinate data systems across the country and slowed down the process of contacting people. The MoH had developed a national automated system for contact tracing which had not been rolled out yet at the time of Verrall's audit.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/national/programmes/checkpoint/audio/2018743380/dr-ayesha-verrall-cautiously-optimistic-about-contact-tracing-improvements|title=Dr Ayesha Verrall cautiously optimistic about contact tracing improvements|date=2020-04-20|website=RNZ|language=en-nz|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Verrall cautioned that although the quality of the contact tracing was good, its scalability remains an issue.<ref name=\":5\" /> The MoH has accepted Verrall's recommendations and have begun implementing them, as well as improving and implementing its nationwide automated contact tracing system, as the country moves to a less strict lockdown measure on 28 April.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/politics/20-04-2020/ardern-announces-alert-level-four-alert-level-three/|title=NZ to exit alert level four after Anzac weekend, Jacinda Ardern reveals|last=Manhire|first=Toby|date=2020-04-20|website=The Spinoff|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>  \n\n=== Selected works and publications ===\n{{Scholia|author}}\n\n* {{Cite journal|last=Verrall|first=Ayesha J.|last2=Alisjahbana|first2=Bachti|last3=Apriani|first3=Lika|last4=Novianty|first4=Novianty|last5=Nurani|first5=Andini C.|last6=van Laarhoven|first6=Arjan|last7=Ussher|first7=James E.|last8=Indrati|first8=Agnes|last9=Ruslami|first9=Rovina|last10=Netea|first10=Mihai G.|last11=Sharples|first11=Katrina|date=2020-03-28|title=Early Clearance of Mycobacterium tuberculosis: The INFECT Case Contact Cohort Study in Indonesia|url=https://academic.oup.com/jid/article/221/8/1351/5531576|journal=The Journal of Infectious Diseases|language=en|volume=221|issue=8|pages=1351\u20131360|doi=10.1093/infdis/jiz168|issn=0022-1899}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Verrall|first=Ayesha J|last2=Chaidir|first2=Lidya|last3=Ruesen|first3=Carolien|last4=Apriani|first4=Lika|last5=Koesoemadinata|first5=Raspati C|last6=van Ingen|first6=Jakko|last7=Sharples|first7=Katrina|last8=van Crevel|first8=Reinout|last9=Alisjahbana|first9=Bachti|last10=Hill|first10=Philip C|last11=on behalf of the INFECT study group|date=2020-01-08|title=Lower BCG Protection Against Mycobacterium tuberculosis Infection After Exposure to Beijing Strains|url=https://www.atsjournals.org/doi/10.1164/rccm.201912-2349LE|journal=American Journal of Respiratory and Critical Care Medicine|language=en|pages=rccm.201912\u20132349LE|doi=10.1164/rccm.201912-2349LE|issn=1073-449X}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Koeken|first=Valerie A. C. M.|last2=Verrall|first2=Ayesha J.|last3=Ardiansyah|first3=Edwin|last4=Apriani|first4=Lika|last5=Santos|first5=J\u00e9ssica C. dos|last6=Kumar|first6=Vinod|last7=Alisjahbana|first7=Bachti|last8=Hill|first8=Philip C.|last9=Joosten|first9=Leo A. B.|last10=Crevel|first10=Reinout van|last11=Laarhoven|first11=Arjan van|date=2020|title=IL-32 and its splice variants are associated with protection against Mycobacterium tuberculosis infection and skewing of Th1/Th17 cytokines|url=https://jlb.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/JLB.4AB0219-071R|journal=Journal of Leukocyte Biology|language=en|volume=107|issue=1|pages=113\u2013118|doi=10.1002/JLB.4AB0219-071R|issn=1938-3673|pmc=PMC6972663|pmid=31378983}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Verrall|first=Ayesha J.|last2=Alisjahbana|first2=Bachti|last3=Apriani|first3=Lika|last4=Novianty|first4=Novianty|last5=Nurani|first5=Andini C.|last6=van Laarhoven|first6=Arjan|last7=Ussher|first7=James E.|last8=Indrati|first8=Agnes|last9=Ruslami|first9=Rovina|last10=Netea|first10=Mihai G.|last11=Sharples|first11=Katrina|date=2020-03-28|title=Early Clearance of Mycobacterium tuberculosis: The INFECT Case Contact Cohort Study in Indonesia|url=https://academic.oup.com/jid/article/221/8/1351/5531576|journal=The Journal of Infectious Diseases|language=en|volume=221|issue=8|pages=1351\u20131360|doi=10.1093/infdis/jiz168|issn=0022-1899}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Steigler|first=Pia|last2=Verrall|first2=Ayesha J.|last3=Kirman|first3=Joanna R.|date=2019|title=Beyond memory T cells: mechanisms of protective immunity to tuberculosis infection|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/imcb.12278|journal=Immunology & Cell Biology|language=en|volume=97|issue=7|pages=647\u2013655|doi=10.1111/imcb.12278|issn=1440-1711}}\n\n=== Awards and honours ===\nVerrall is [[Fellow]] of the [[Royal Australasian College of Physicians]] (FRACP).\n\nThe Verrall Award given by the New Zealand Medical Student Journal is named after her, to honour her efforts to form and secure funding for the journal in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nzmsj.com/verrall-award.html|title=Verrall Award|website=New Zealand Medical Student Journal|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Physician and infectious diseases researcher}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ayesha Verrall\n| image              = \n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| other_names        = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place        = [[Invercargill]]\n| nationality        = [[New Zealand]]\n| education          = [[University of Otago]]\n| occupation         = Infectious diseases physician and researcher\n| years_active       = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Ayesha Jennifer Verrall''' is a [[New Zealand]] [[Infectious disease (medical specialty)|infectious diseases]] physician and researcher with expertise in [[tuberculosis]] and [[international health]]. She is also a senior lecturer at the [[University of Otago]], [[Wellington]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.otago.ac.nz/healthsciences/expertise/Profile/index.html?id=1377|title=Dr Ayesha Verrall {{!}} Division of Health Sciences|last=|first=|date=|website=otago.ac.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019-20 coronavirus epidemic]], she provided the New Zealand [[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]] with an independent review and recommendations for its [[contact tracing]] approach to COVID-19 cases.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.health.govt.nz/publication/rapid-audit-contact-tracing-covid-19-new-zealand|title=Rapid Audit of Contact Tracing for COVID-19 in New Zealand|last=Verrall|first=Ayesha|date=2020-04-20|website=|publisher=[[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>  \n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nVerrall was born in [[Invercargill]] and raised in [[Te Anau]]. Her mother is from the [[Maldives]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Gibb|first=John|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/natural-immunity-solving-tb-mystery|title=Natural immunity: solving a Tb mystery|date=2014-11-08|work=Otago Daily Times|access-date=2020-04-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nVerrall trained in medicine at the [[University of Otago Dunedin School of Medicine]], where she obtained her [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery (MBChB)]] in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.otago.ac.nz/careers/otago067425.html|title=Ayesha Verrall|last=|first=|date=|website=Career Development Centre {{!}} otago.ac.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>  She was president of the [[Otago University Students' Association]] in 2001<ref name=\":2\" /> and in 2003 also led a group of medical students to form the New Zealand Medical Student Journal (NSMJ).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nzmsj.com/history.html|title=History|website=New Zealand Medical Student Journal|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> During the next decade, Verrall trained in [[tropical medicine]], [[bioethics]] and [[international health]] in Singapore, USA and Peru.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/graduate-funded-tb-study|title=Graduate funded for Tb study|last=Gibb|first=John|date=2012-11-28|website=Otago Daily Times Online News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Verrall earned a Diploma in Tropical Medicine and Hygiene from the [[Instituto Conmemorativo Gorgas de Estudios de la Salud|Gorgas Institute]] in [[Lima|Lima, Peru]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.otago.ac.nz/internationalhealth/otago661680.html|title=Dr Ayesha Verrall {{!}} Centre for International Health|last=|first=|date=|website=otago.ac.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Verrall completed her PhD in [[Epidemiology of tuberculosis|tuberculosis epidemiology]] at the University of Otago, in collaboration with [[Padjadjaran University]] in [[Indonesia]] and [[Radboud University Nijmegen]] in the [[Netherlands]]. Her research investigated the early clearance immune response of the [[Mycobacterium tuberculosis]] infection among Indonesian people who were highly exposed to the bacteria, yet remained uninfected.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite thesis|title=Innate Factors in Early Clearance of Mycobacterium tuberculosis|url=https://ourarchive.otago.ac.nz/handle/10523/7999|publisher=University of Otago|date=2018|degree=Thesis|language=en|first=Ayesha Jennifer|last=Verrall}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nVerrall is a senior lecturer at [[University of Otago]] in the Department of Pathology and Molecular Medicine. She teaches microbiology to medical students and researches tuberculosis epidemiology and immunology.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nVerrall is also an infectious diseases physician at the [[Capital and Coast District Health Board]] in Wellington and became an elected member of its board in 2019 where she currently serves as deputy board chair. She also provides advise to the government on vaccines, outbreaks and disease prevention. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ccdhb.org.nz/about-us/our-board/|title=CCDHB Board Members|last=|first=|date=|website=ccdhb.org.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> During the [[2019\u20132020 New Zealand measles outbreak]], she advocated for a more strategic approach for allocating more government funding and resources towards increasing vaccination rates for measles, as well as preventing future outbreaks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/112695463/concerted-effort-needed-to-increase-measles-vaccinations-and-prevent-further-outbreaks--expert|title=Concerted effort needed to increase measles vaccinations and prevent further outbreaks - expert|last=Macandrew|first=Ruby|date=2019-05-14|website=Stuff|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, during the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Verrall called for the the New Zealand Government to urgently improve their data on community spread of the coronavirus disease [[COVID-19]] through expanding the testing criteria beyond sick people, increasing laboratory testing and contact tracing capabilities. At the time, the Ministry of Health (MoH) was tracing the contacts of 50 cases per day; Verrall called for up to a 1000 people's contacts to be traced every day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/03/coronavirus-doctors-warn-of-blind-spot-in-government-s-covid-19-response-plan.html|title=Coronavirus: Doctors warn of blind spot in Government's COVID-19 response plan|work=Newshub|access-date=2020-04-21|language=en}}</ref>  \n\nSubsequently, Verrall was commissioned by the MoH to provide an independent audit of its contact tracing programme.<ref name=\":1\" /> The report was initially submitted to the MoH in early April and made publicly available on 20 April to allow the government time to respond and implement some of the recommendations.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Davison|first=Isaac|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12325778|title=Covid 19 coronavirus: Scientists sound level 3, contact tracing alarm bells|date=2020-04-18|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2020-04-21|url-status=live|last2=Johnston|first2=Kirsty|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/04/coronavirus-dr-bloomfield-announces-advancements-in-contact-tracing.html|title=Coronavirus: Dr Bloomfield announces advancements in contact tracing|date=|work=Newshub|access-date=2020-04-22|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> Verrall's audit identified shortcomings in the health sector's approach, which was \"understaffed and lacked cohesion\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/04/contact-tracing-audit-exposes-significant-shortcomings-in-health-system.html|title=Contact tracing audit exposes significant shortcomings in health system|date=|work=Newshub|access-date=2020-04-22|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> The country's 12 \"devolved\" public health units (PHUs) made it difficult to coordinate data systems across the country and slowed down the process of contacting people. The MoH had developed a national automated system for contact tracing which had not been rolled out yet at the time of Verrall's audit.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/national/programmes/checkpoint/audio/2018743380/dr-ayesha-verrall-cautiously-optimistic-about-contact-tracing-improvements|title=Dr Ayesha Verrall cautiously optimistic about contact tracing improvements|date=2020-04-20|website=RNZ|language=en-nz|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Verrall cautioned that although the quality of the contact tracing was good, its scalability remains an issue.<ref name=\":5\" /> The MoH has accepted Verrall's recommendations and have begun implementing them, as well as improving and implementing its nationwide automated contact tracing system, as the country moves to a less strict lockdown measure on 28 April.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/politics/20-04-2020/ardern-announces-alert-level-four-alert-level-three/|title=NZ to exit alert level four after Anzac weekend, Jacinda Ardern reveals|last=Manhire|first=Toby|date=2020-04-20|website=The Spinoff|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>  \n\n== Selected works and publications ==\n{{Scholia|author}}\n\n* {{Cite journal|last=Verrall|first=Ayesha J.|last2=Alisjahbana|first2=Bachti|last3=Apriani|first3=Lika|last4=Novianty|first4=Novianty|last5=Nurani|first5=Andini C.|last6=van Laarhoven|first6=Arjan|last7=Ussher|first7=James E.|last8=Indrati|first8=Agnes|last9=Ruslami|first9=Rovina|last10=Netea|first10=Mihai G.|last11=Sharples|first11=Katrina|date=2020-03-28|title=Early Clearance of Mycobacterium tuberculosis: The INFECT Case Contact Cohort Study in Indonesia|url=https://academic.oup.com/jid/article/221/8/1351/5531576|journal=The Journal of Infectious Diseases|language=en|volume=221|issue=8|pages=1351\u20131360|doi=10.1093/infdis/jiz168|issn=0022-1899}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Verrall|first=Ayesha J|last2=Chaidir|first2=Lidya|last3=Ruesen|first3=Carolien|last4=Apriani|first4=Lika|last5=Koesoemadinata|first5=Raspati C|last6=van Ingen|first6=Jakko|last7=Sharples|first7=Katrina|last8=van Crevel|first8=Reinout|last9=Alisjahbana|first9=Bachti|last10=Hill|first10=Philip C|last11=on behalf of the INFECT study group|date=2020-01-08|title=Lower BCG Protection Against Mycobacterium tuberculosis Infection After Exposure to Beijing Strains|url=https://www.atsjournals.org/doi/10.1164/rccm.201912-2349LE|journal=American Journal of Respiratory and Critical Care Medicine|language=en|pages=rccm.201912\u20132349LE|doi=10.1164/rccm.201912-2349LE|issn=1073-449X}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Koeken|first=Valerie A. C. M.|last2=Verrall|first2=Ayesha J.|last3=Ardiansyah|first3=Edwin|last4=Apriani|first4=Lika|last5=Santos|first5=J\u00e9ssica C. dos|last6=Kumar|first6=Vinod|last7=Alisjahbana|first7=Bachti|last8=Hill|first8=Philip C.|last9=Joosten|first9=Leo A. B.|last10=Crevel|first10=Reinout van|last11=Laarhoven|first11=Arjan van|date=2020|title=IL-32 and its splice variants are associated with protection against Mycobacterium tuberculosis infection and skewing of Th1/Th17 cytokines|url=https://jlb.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/JLB.4AB0219-071R|journal=Journal of Leukocyte Biology|language=en|volume=107|issue=1|pages=113\u2013118|doi=10.1002/JLB.4AB0219-071R|issn=1938-3673|pmc=PMC6972663|pmid=31378983}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Verrall|first=Ayesha J.|last2=Alisjahbana|first2=Bachti|last3=Apriani|first3=Lika|last4=Novianty|first4=Novianty|last5=Nurani|first5=Andini C.|last6=van Laarhoven|first6=Arjan|last7=Ussher|first7=James E.|last8=Indrati|first8=Agnes|last9=Ruslami|first9=Rovina|last10=Netea|first10=Mihai G.|last11=Sharples|first11=Katrina|date=2020-03-28|title=Early Clearance of Mycobacterium tuberculosis: The INFECT Case Contact Cohort Study in Indonesia|url=https://academic.oup.com/jid/article/221/8/1351/5531576|journal=The Journal of Infectious Diseases|language=en|volume=221|issue=8|pages=1351\u20131360|doi=10.1093/infdis/jiz168|issn=0022-1899}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Steigler|first=Pia|last2=Verrall|first2=Ayesha J.|last3=Kirman|first3=Joanna R.|date=2019|title=Beyond memory T cells: mechanisms of protective immunity to tuberculosis infection|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/imcb.12278|journal=Immunology & Cell Biology|language=en|volume=97|issue=7|pages=647\u2013655|doi=10.1111/imcb.12278|issn=1440-1711}}\n\n== Awards and honours ==\nVerrall is [[Fellow]] of the [[Royal Australasian College of Physicians]] (FRACP).\n\nThe Verrall Award given by the New Zealand Medical Student Journal is named after her, to honour her efforts to form and secure funding for the journal in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nzmsj.com/verrall-award.html|title=Verrall Award|website=New Zealand Medical Student Journal|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n", "name_user": "Drpriaero", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed headings to subheadings and added post-nominals", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ayesha_Verrall"}
{"title_page": "Warrior (Kesha album)", "text_new": "{{short description|2012 Kesha album}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Warrior\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Kesha]]\n| cover      = Kesha_Warrior.jpeg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Standard edition album cover\n| released   = {{start date|2012|11|30}}\n| recorded   = January\u2013August 2012\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Electropop]]<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n*[[Rock music|rock]]<ref name=\"rollingstone\"/>\n}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=44|s=27}}<br>{{duration|m=58|s=43}} <small>(Deluxe edition)</small>\n| label      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Kemosabe Records|Kemosabe]]\n*[[RCA Records|RCA]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*[[Ammo (musician)|Ammo]]\n*[[Benny Blanco]]\n*Billboard\n*[[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]]\n*[[Dr. Luke]] (also [[Executive producer|exec.]])\n*[[Greg Kurstin]]\n*[[Kool Kojak]]\n*[[Matt Squire]]\n*[[Max Martin]]\n*[[Shellback (record producer)|Shellback]]\n*[[Stardeath and White Dwarfs]]\n*[[Steven Wolf]]\n*[[The Flaming Lips]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[I Am the Dance Commander + I Command You to Dance: The Remix Album]]\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[#Deconstructed|Deconstructed]]\n| next_year  = 2012\n| misc         = {{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[Kesha]] studio album\n| type = studio\n| prev_title = [[Animal (Kesha album)|Animal]]\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| title      = Warrior\n| year       = 2012\n| next_title = [[Rainbow (Kesha album)|Rainbow]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = Warrior\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Die Young (Kesha song)|Die Young]]\n | single1date = September 25, 2012\n | single2     = [[C'Mon (Kesha song)|C'Mon]]\n | single2date = November 16, 2012\n | single3     = [[Crazy Kids]]\n | single3date = April 30, 2013\n}}\n}}\n\n''''' Warrior''''' is the second [[studio album]] by American singer [[Kesha]], released on November 30, 2012 by [[Kemosabe Records|Kemosabe]] and [[RCA Records]]. Its music incorporates a wide range of genres, including [[Pop music|pop]], [[Electronic dance music|EDM]], [[Rock music|rock]], [[Pop punk|punk]], [[Hip hop music|rap]], [[Country music|country]], and [[Ballad music|balladry]]. Kesha described the album as more personal than her previous material in addition to mentioning it was her attempt at reviving the rock genre, calling it a \"[[cock rock|cock pop]]\" record. Its theme is said to be [[Magic (supernatural)|magic]].\n\nWriting for ''Warrior'' began in late 2011 and ended in early 2012, with recording taking place from January through August 2012. Kesha wrote the majority of the album while touring internationally and during her [[spiritual journey]]. Contributions to the album's production came from longtime collaborators [[Dr. Luke]] (who was also the [[executive producer]] of the project), [[Max Martin]], [[Shellback (record producer)|Shellback]], [[Ammo (musician)|Ammo]] and [[Benny Blanco]]. It features guest vocals from American rock singer [[Iggy Pop]], who has been cited as a major influence on the album, as well as writing contributions from [[Nate Ruess]] from American [[indie rock]] trio [[Fun (band)|Fun]], American [[rapper]] [[will.i.am]], American [[singer-songwriter]] [[Bonnie McKee]], [[The Black Keys]] drummer [[Patrick Carney]], American rock bands [[The Strokes]] and [[The Flaming Lips]] and Kesha's own mother, [[Pebe Sebert]]. Upon its release, ''Warrior'' received generally favorable reviews from music critics, who commended its rock-influenced material, lyrical content, and collaborations, whilst others criticized its use of [[Auto-Tune]] and formulaic content. The album reached number 6 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart in the United States, while also charting in Australia, Canada, Japan, the United Kingdom, and other countries.\n\nThe album's lead single \"[[Die Young (Kesha song)|Die Young]]\" achieved commercial success, peaking at number 2 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart in the United States, while also charting in multiple countries worldwide. \"[[C'Mon (Kesha song)|C'Mon]]\" initially served as a [[promotional single]], and peaked at number 27 in the US after its release as the album's second single. An [[acoustic music|acoustic]] [[extended play]] (EP), ''[[Deconstructed (EP)|Deconstructed]]'' (2012), was released exclusively through Kesha's website to promote the fan edition of the album and features rerecorded songs from her previous releases as well as a cover of \"[[Old Flames Can't Hold a Candle to You]]\" (1980) by American [[country music|country]] recording artist [[Dolly Parton]] and cowritten by Kesha's mother, Pebe. \"[[Crazy Kids]]\" was released as the third and final single from ''Warrior''. In total, the album spawned three Top 40 hits in the US, Canada, and Australia. To promote the album, Kesha embarked on two concert tours: the first was the [[North American Tour 2013]], coheadlined with American rapper [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]], and the second one was the [[Warrior Tour]] (2013\u20132015).\n\n==Background==\nIn June 2010, Kesha discussed her second studio album with [[MTV News]]. During the interview she revealed that she was already beginning to think about her second album and explained that it was going differ from her first record, specifically commenting that it would reflect her growth: \"There's definitely going to be a difference. I'm always changing and evolving and because I write all of my own music it will be reflective of the record. It'll still stay fun and young and irreverent.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com.au/news/23341d5a-kesha-new-album/|title=The Singer Reveals Details About Her Follow-Up Record|date=June 10, 2010|author=Barnett, Sophie|publisher=[[MTV News]]. [[MTV Networks]] ([[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]])|accessdate=June 11, 2010}}</ref> After the release of her first album Kesha embarked on her first worldwide tour, the [[Get Sleazy Tour]] throughout 2011. While touring she began writing songs for her second album but recording and other work on the album was not commenced until she had completed the tour.<ref name=\"Wango\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2011/02/keha-talks-u-tour-its-epic-dance-party/|title=Ke$ha Talks U.$. Tour: \"It's an Epic Dance Party\"|author=O'Donnell, Kevin|date=February 11, 2011|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|publisher=Spin Media|accessdate=March 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the singer took a hiatus from music to embark on other ventures.<ref name=\"VMag p2\" /> She was hired by the [[Humane Society]] and became their first global ambassador, which consumed her time as she made a documentary for [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]] that revolved around \"animals being abused and how to stop that, or animals that are going extinct and how to help those animals.\"<ref name=\"VMag p2\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.vmagazine.com/2012/04/born-in-the-u-s-a/?page=2|title=Born In The U.$.A|author=Sandberg, Patrik|page=2|magazine=[[V (American magazine)|V magazine]]|accessdate=May 1, 2012|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BrMauzDT?url=http://www.vmagazine.com/2012/04/born-in-the-u-s-a/?page=2|archive-date=November 1, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album includes a variety of different musical participants, which was explained by the singer: \"The range of artists I want to work with is so vast it\u2019s bizarre. If someone is a real artist, you can\u2019t confine them to a particular genre. It\u2019s my mission to make it all make sense somehow.\"<ref name=\"VMag Page3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vmagazine.com/2012/04/born-in-the-u-s-a/?page=3|title=Born In The U.$.A|author=Sandberg, Patrik|page=3|publisher=V magazine|accessdate=May 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120803005809/http://www.vmagazine.com/2012/04/born-in-the-u-s-a/?page=3|archive-date=August 3, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Along with expanding her collaborations, the singer expanded her musical repertoire, as she began playing the guitar significantly more with the plans of incorporating it into her new material.<ref name=\"Lewis1\" /> In February 2012, while being interviewed by [[Glamour (magazine)|''Glamour'']], Kesha stated that while she was currently in the process of writing songs for her album, she was also taking a variety of instrument lessons, emphasizing specifically that she was taking guitar lessons.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.glamour.com/entertainment/2012/02/kesha-the-real-girl-under-the-glitter-glamour-march-2012|title=Ke$ha: There\u2019s a Real Girl Underneath All That Glitter|author=Hill, Logan|date=February 2012|magazine=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]. [[Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications]]|accessdate=February 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Title and concept==\nIn March 2011, Kesha revealed in an interview with ''Beatweek Magazine'' that she had already chosen the title for the record, naming it ''Spandex on the Distant Horizon''.<ref name=\"Beatweek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beatweek.com/news/8287-keha-reveals-her-next-album-title-spandex-on-the-distant-horizon/|title=Ke$ha reveals her next album title: Spandex on the Distant Horizon|date=March 8, 2011|publisher=Beatweek Magazine|accessdate=July 14, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BrMiLYyL?url=http://www.beatweek.com/news/8287-keha-reveals-her-next-album-title-spandex-on-the-distant-horizon/|archive-date=November 1, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, in a publication in May 2012, ''Billboard'' stated that the project was untitled.<ref name=\"Maloy\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-hook/489238/keha-wants-collabs-with-bieber-keith-richards-goes-americana-for-v|title=Ke$ha Wants Collabs With Bieber & Keith Richards, Goes Americana for V Magazine Cover |date=May 2, 2012|author1=Maloy, Sarah |author2=DelliCarpini Jr., Gregory |work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=May 2, 2012}}</ref> The album's underlying theme stems around embracing a person's inner [[warrior]], which the singer elaborated on: \"I\u2019ve seen how many people my music can reach, and I\u2019ve realized that I have somewhat of a social responsibility to make sure everything I say is positive. The underlying theme of this next record is warrior, with the positive message being that everyone has a warrior inside.\"<ref name=\"VMag p2\" /> On September 18, 2012, via her Twitter and [[Instagram]] accounts, Kesha began announcing letters, believed to be from the title of the album, alluding to the name of the album title, \"Warrior\". This was later confirmed when she tweeted the release date of the album.<ref name=\"bigpond\">{{cite web|title=Kesha's new single could feature Rihanna|url=http://wap.news.bigpond.com/articles/Entertainment/2012/09/19/Keshas_new_single_could_feature_Rihanna_796772.html|work=[[BigPond]]|publisher=[[Telstra]]|accessdate=October 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nKesha worked with [[Lukasz Gottwald]] and [[Max Martin]] on a variety of tracks.<ref name=\"Lewis1\" /> She also expressed interest in enlisting the production duo, the [[Dust Brothers]], who are known for producing tracks for the [[Rolling Stones]], the [[Beastie Boys]] and [[Beck]], however no recording dates were ever penned. Her friend Paul Nicholls, a DJ, was also named as a potential participant in construction of the album. However, no recording dates with him have been recorded either.<ref name=\"Lewis1\" /> According to [[MTV]], Kesha entered the studio with Luke in January 2012. Both Kesha and Luke had been working on material for the upcoming project but had yet to start studio sessions prior to January.<ref name=\"JocyelynIntewview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1676580/kesha-2012-new-album.jhtml|title=Ke$ha Looks Forward To An 'Absolutely Crazy' 2012 'People say that rock and roll is dead, and it is my mission and my goal to resurrect it,' singer says of her next album.|author=Vena,Jocyelyn|date=January 3, 2012|work=MTV News| publisher=MTV Networks (Viacom)|accessdate=January 3, 2012}}</ref> Kesha reported via [[Twitter]] in March 2012 she was recording the album with Luke and Benny Blanco. In the recording studio together they created a track described by the singer as a \"cock-pop\" influenced song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.ca/music/news/a371156/keha-making-ck-pop-music-on-new-album.html|title=Ke$ha making \"c**k pop\" music on new album|author=Copsey, Robert|date=March 14, 2012|work=Digital Spy|publisher=[[Hachette Filipacchi UK]]|accessdate=March 14, 2012}}</ref> This track was revealed to be \"Thinking of You\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.nme.com/news/keha/62623|title=Ke$ha: 'My new album is the dawn of cock pop' Singer reckons she's introduced a whole new genre...|date=March 14, 2012|author=Staff|magazine=NME|accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wayne Coyne outside Wal-Mart.jpg|left|thumb|150px|[[Wayne Coyne]] of American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[The Flaming Lips]] contributed to the album after learning Kesha was a fan of his work and after she worked on his band's album ''[[Flaming Lips and Heady Fwends]]'' (2012).]]\n{{Quote box\n| width = 30%\n| align = right\n| quote = \"I'm helping with some lyrics here and there. She's really a great songwriter. She has an easy way with things. I've worked with a lot of people that are very uptight about how they do their music, but she's very fun, so I don't really have any reservations about whether I don't like her music. I like her, and she likes us, so fuck it. I'm not too worried about it.\"<ref name=\"Fitzmaurice\"/>\n| source = \u2014Coyne, on writing and working with Kesha.\n}} \n[[Wayne Coyne]] from The Flaming Lips first expressed interest in working with Kesha in January 2012. Coyne said he knew she was a fan of his work and felt that a collaboration between the two would be a \"perfect match.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/bon-iver-confirmed-for-flaming-lips-covers-album-20120112|title=Bon Iver Confirmed for Flaming Lips Album. Frontman Wayne Coyne hopeful Ke$ha, Erykah Badu will also commit in time for an April release|author=Hyman, Dan|date=January 12, 2012|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner]]|accessdate=February 29, 2012}}</ref> The duo reportedly collaborated at the Lips' studio in January 2012.<ref name=\"Marc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2012/01/keha-glitter-bombs-flaming-lips-studio/|title=Ke$ha Glitter Bombs the Flaming Lips' Studio|author=Hogan, Marc|date=January 23, 2012|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|publisher=Spin Media LLC|accessdate=February 29, 2012}}</ref> A track called \"2012\" was created during a February recording session in Nashville and was released on the Lips' album, ''[[The Flaming Lips and Heady Fwends]]''. In March 2012, Coyne told ''Rolling Stone'' that he was in the development stages of talking to Kesha about working with her on her new material.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/wayne-coyne-in-talks-to-collaborate-on-ke-has-new-lp-20120328|title=Wayne Coyne in Talks to Collaborate on Ke$ha's New LP|author=Hyman, Dan|date=March 28, 2012|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner]]|accessdate=March 28, 2012}}</ref> Along with \"2012\", Wayne and Kesha's first collaboration created three other songs, all of which belonged to Kesha. Coyne was later asked if he still intended to contribute to her album he responded, stating: \"I'm trying to. I think we're getting together right before Easter. We've already done three songs-- they're hers\".<ref name=\"Fitzmaurice\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/46048-wayne-coyne-talks-new-flaming-lips-album-working-with-keha-and-coldplay-blood/|title=Wayne Coyne Talks New Flaming Lips Album, Working With Ke$ha and Coldplay, Blood|author=Fitzmaurice, Larry|date=April 5, 2012|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> According to Twitter messages by Coyne, recording between the duo continued in April 2012 and a track that discussed \"futuristic sex toys\" was created.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-flaming-lips/63152|title=The Flaming Lips and Ke$ha recording song about 'futuristic sex toys' |date=April 10, 2012|author=Staff|magazine=NME|accessdate=April 10, 2012}}</ref> Coyne and Kesha revealed via Twitter that a song titled \"You Control My Heart\" was created. Coyne announced that he was in the process of [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]] the song.<ref name=\"PopCrush YCMH\">{{cite web|url=http://popcrush.com/snippets-kesha-wayne-coyne-collabo-you-control-my-heart/|title=Snippets From Kesha + Wayne Coyne Collabo \u2018You Control My Heart\u2019 Released|author=Maher, Cristin|date=April 18, 2012|publisher=Popcrush. Townsquare Media, LLC|accessdate=April 18, 2012}}</ref> \"Past Lives\", a track described by Coyne as a \"stellar track\" was confirmed to be another collaboration between the pair.<ref name=\"Mxdwn Past Lives\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mxdwn.com/2012/08/16/topstory/wayne-coyne-speaks-on-title-of-new-flaming-lips-album-taking-drugs-and-making-a-king-crimson-cover-album/|title=Wayne Coyne Speaks on Title of New Flaming Lips Album, Taking Drugs and Making a King Crimson Cover Album|date=August 16, 2012|publisher=mxdwn.com|accessdate=August 16, 2012|quote=\"I think at the moment, I think there\u2019s one pretty stellar track. It\u2019s her song, but where we\u2019ve done some production. I think on the 21st of this month we\u2019re going in with Ben Folds, between us all we\u2019re coming up with a giant string arrangement that\u2019s going to go on that, we\u2019re going to record that... It is called, I think at the moment it\u2019s called \u201cPast Life.\u201d}}</ref> Altogether, Coyne and Kesha's collaboration yielded between six and seven tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1685827/kesha-flaming-lips-tattoo.jhtml|title=Ke$ha Gives Flaming Lips Frontman His First-Ever Toe Tattoo. Wayne Coyne talks about what happens when you work with 'freaks' like Ke$ha on The Flaming Lips and Heady Fwends.|date=April 24, 2012|author=Montgomery, James|publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks (Viacom)|accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn mid April 2012, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' published an article claiming that Scottish producer [[Calvin Harris]] had contributed several tracks to the upcoming album. Their specific recording date was unknown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/495316/calvin-harris-is-done-singing-lead-despite-solo-hits|first=Andrew|last=Hampp|title=Calvin Harris Is Done Singing Lead, Despite Solo Hits|date=April 13, 2012|accessdate=April 13, 2012|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415230811/http://www.billboard.com/news/calvin-harris-is-done-singing-lead-despite-1006758152.story|archivedate=April 15, 2012 }}</ref> In May 2012, Kesha continued to record with Dr. Luke, and artist [[Sia Furler]], although this track did not make the final track listing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.ca/music/news/a382493/keha-working-with-sia-on-new-material.html|title=Ke$ha working with Sia on new material|author=Colin, Daniels|date=May 19, 2012|work=Digital Spy|publisher=Hachette Filipacchi UK|accessdate=May 19, 2012}}</ref> Rock singer Iggy Pop was also revealed as a collaborator, when the singer tweeted a picture in May 2012 saying that the singer would feature on the record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.ca/music/news/a380729/keha-confirms-iggy-pop-collaboration-for-new-album.html|title=Ke$ha confirms Iggy Pop collaboration for new album|author=Cospey, Robert|date=May 9, 2012|work=Digital Spy|publisher=Hachette Filipacchi UK|accessdate=May 19, 2012}}</ref> ''Billboard'' later confirmed Iggy Pop would feature on \"Dirty Love\", produced by Dr. Luke.<ref name=\"Dirty Love Iggy Pop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/480615/keha-really-close-to-finishing-album|title=Ke$ha 'Really Close' to Finishing Album|date=August 3, 2012|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]}}</ref> Kesha continued to work with Dr Luke and Benny Blanco, and with new collaborators [[Cirkut (producer)|Henry Walter]] and [[Fun (band)|Fun.]] lead singer Nate Ruess \u2013 the four created a track described by Blanco as \"old hippie rock\".<ref name=\"Blanco Die Young\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/pop-hitmaker-beny-blanco-talks-payphone-success-ke-has-new-sound-20120717|title=Pop Hitmaker Benny Blanco Talks 'Payphone' Success, Ke$ha's New Sound|author=Stephen, Horowitz|date=July 17, 2012|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=July 17, 2012}}</ref> That track was later revealed as \"Die Young\".<ref name=\"Die Young BMI\">{{cite web|url=http://repertoire.bmi.com/title.asp?blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&keyID=14785259&ShowNbr=0&ShowSeqNbr=0&querytype=WorkID|title=BMI - Repertoire Search<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=Repertoire.bmi.com|accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref> Kesha revealed that she and Dr Luke had created 17 incomplete songs, including \"Last Goodbye\", \"Die Young\" and \"Supernatural\". She commented on the sound, \"I want it to be a mix of what works on the radio and what I listen to in my spare time,\" she says. \"I'm on a steady diet of T. Rex and Iggy Pop.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/massive-beats-wild-nights-and-crazy-tattoos-ke-ha-rocks-out-on-new-album-20120720|title=Massive Beats, Wild Nights and Crazy Tattoos: Ke$ha Rocks Out on New Album: T. Rex, Iggy Pop, Neil Young inspire pop star's second full-length album|author=Edwards, Gavin|date=July 20, 2012|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner]]|accessdate=July 20, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Rolling Stone magazine\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1690089/kesha-rolling-stone-album.jhtml|title=Ke$ha 'Gives So Many F\u2014s' About Her New Album 'On this record, I said, 'Let's leave the tricks to a minimum and let me wail,' ' Ke$ha tells Rolling Stone about her 'vulnerable' album|author=Montgomery, James|date=July 20, 2012|work=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=July 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n[[File:Iggy Pop - pinkpop87.jpg|right|thumb|170px|[[Iggy Pop]]'s debut solo album [[The Idiot (album)|''The Idiot'']] (1977), was cited as one of the album's main musical influences when Kesha was constructing the album's sound.]]\nIn contrast to her debut album ''[[Animal (Kesha album)|Animal]]'' (2010), Kesha stated her second album would also incorporate [[Rock music|rock]] genres, inspired from the music of the [[80's rock|1970s]].<ref name=\"Wango\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1663946/kesha-new-album.jhtml|title=Ke$ha Is Channeling 'Sexiness' Of '70s Rock For New Album|author=Montgomery, James|date=May 16, 2011|work=MTV News| publisher=Viacom|accessdate=June 5, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Lewis1\" /> 1970s rock singers [[Led Zeppelin]], [[AC/DC]] and Iggy Pop's album, ''[[The Idiot (album)|The Idiot]]'', were cited as musical inspirations for the next record.<ref name=\"Lewis1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.ca/music/interviews/a326631/keha-interview-i-want-to-be-fking-perfect.html|title=Ke$ha interview: \"I want to be f**king perfect\"|author=Corner, Lewis|date=July 4, 2011|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hachette Filipacchi UK]]|accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref> Kesha stated in press that she intended to incorporate a confluence of genres, including [[blues music]], saying, \"I definitely want the next record to be experimental and I would love to play with all the different sounds of the music I listen to. I really want some dirty guitar and I wouldn't mind if there were elements of blues.\"<ref name=\"Lewis1\" /> On her first record Kesha imposed a restriction on her producers limiting their use of guitars.<ref name=\"VMag Page3\" /> In order to encompass \"visceral\" energy on the record she lifted this restriction and instead has chosen to focus on the inclusion of guitars to try and capture the sound of the 1970s and '80s.<ref name=\"VMag Page3\" /> Commenting on the album before its release, she said: \"Some people will be shocked [by it]. Some will also be excited to know that I don\u2019t just do silly white-girl rap. I'm from the South, I have a lot of soul. But trust me\u2014it's not going to be some [[avant-garde]] [[jazz]] record. I innately write [[Pop music|pop]] songs. That's just what I do.\"<ref name=\"VMag p2\" />\n\nKesha began recording the album in 2011, after traveling the world; she went on a [[spiritual journey]]. Recalling experiences of feeding baby lions and swimming with [[great white shark]]s, Kesha said, \"I got hypnotized, and I just really wanted this record to be really positive, really raw, really vulnerable and about the magic of life.\"<ref name=\"huffpost\">{{cite news|title=Ke$ha 'Die Young' Hits Airwaves, Party Anthem Boasts Stripped, 'Hippie Rock' Sound|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/25/kesha-die-young-new-song-new-album-listen_n_1912850.html|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|accessdate=October 1, 2012|first=Cavan|last=Sieczkowski|date=September 25, 2012}}</ref> \"Supernatural\" contains [[dubstep]] elements and explores erotic experiences Kesha encountered with [[ghost]]s.<ref name=\"fox\">{{cite news|title=Ke$ha says she had 'sexy' experiences with a ghost: Who is the most 'out there' celebrity?|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/09/27/keha-says-had-exy-experiences-with-ghost-who-is-most-out-there-celebrity/|work=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=October 17, 2012|date=September 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ke$ha Admits To Having Sex With A Ghost|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/keha/365315-keha-sex-ghost-rihanna-new-album-warrior|work=MTV|publisher=Viacom|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ke$ha reveals she had sex with a ghost|url=http://www.nme.com/news/keha/66332|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref> The track \"Dirty Love\" was inspired by Iggy Pop's music and draws from [[garage rock]] and [[punk rock]].<ref name=\"popcrushiggy\">{{cite web|last=Sager|first=Jessica|url=http://popcrush.com/kesha-iggy-pop-duet-dirty-love/|title=Kesha + Iggy Pop Duet \u2018Dirty Love\u2019 Leaks|work=Pop Crush|accessdate=March 22, 2013|date=November 27, 2012}}</ref> \"Wonderland\" is a [[country rock|country-rock]] song that explores Kesha's past with her broke friends.<ref name=\"hollywoodrock\">{{cite news|last=Powell|first=Nicole|title=Ke$ha's 'Warrior': What the Critics Are Saying|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kehas-warrior-what-critics-are-397820|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=March 22, 2013}}</ref><ref name=billboardtbt/> The tracks \"Wherever You Are,\" \"Die Young,\" \"C'Mon\" all contain elements of [[Synthpop|technopop]],<ref name=\"avclub\">{{cite web|last=Zaleski|first=Annie|title=Ke$ha: Warrior - Review|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/keha-warrior,89338/|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|accessdate=March 22, 2013|date=December 4, 2012}}</ref> whereas tracks like \"Only Wanna Dance With You\" and \"Gold Trans Am\" draw from [[electronic rock]].{{citation needed|date=January 2013}} \"C'Mon\" and \"Crazy Kids\" are [[Electro (music)|electronic]] rap songs.<ref name=billboardtbt/> Overall, Kesha said the theme of ''Warrior'' is [[magic (paranormal)|magic]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ke$ha Says She Had Sex With A Ghost|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/27/kesha-sex-with-ghost_n_1919320.html|work=The Huffington Post|publisher=AOL|accessdate=October 17, 2012|first=Stephanie|last=Marcus|date=September 27, 2012}}</ref> She further explained the main inspiration behind the album's change of sound:\n<blockquote>\"I feel like I don't necessarily agree, but people say that [[rock and roll]] is dead, and it is my mission and my goal to resurrect it in the form of my pop music, [...] that's the goal. We'll see what happens. That's a very ambitious and lofty goal, but that's my goal.\"<ref name=\"JocyelynIntewview\"/></blockquote>\n\n==Songs and lyrics==\n{{Listen|pos=left|filename=Kesha Supernatural (snippet).ogg|title=\"Supernatural\"|format1=[[Ogg]]|description=\"Supernatural\" contains [[dubstep]] elements and explores erotic experiences Kesha encountered with [[ghost]]s.}}\nKesha has said the songs are inspired by her experiences during her tours.<ref name=\"Lewis1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/playlist/view/197673/Dream-for-Ke-ha/|title=Dream For Ke$ha|last=Dawson|first=Kim|last2=Cabooter|first2=James|date=June 25, 2011|work=[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]|publisher=Northern and Shell Media Publications|accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref> In contrast to her first record which featured music described by the singer as \"very brash and very sassy and very unapologetic and irreverent\", she says the second album makes a lyrical departure and explores a more vulnerable side in its lyrics.<ref name=\"JocyelynIntewview\"/> She explained: \"I have learned over the past three years of doing this that being vulnerable doesn't mean you're weak. I very much want to be seen as a strong woman, but I realize that vulnerability can also be a strength. So on my next record, you are going to hear probably a little more of that.\"<ref name=\"JocyelynIntewview\"/> Kesha commented, in an interview with ''Rolling Stone'', \"The first two records talked more about partying, which is a great, magical part of life, but some songs on the new record are more personal and vulnerable. And you can hear more of the music I listen to when I'm lying in my bed. I'm not claiming that it's a rock record \u2013 but as long as it's fucking good, you can call it whatever you want.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/> Co-written by her mother, Pebe Sebert, the song titled \"Gold Trans Am\" doubles as a [[metaphor]] for her [[vagina]] and alludes to her [[Pontiac Firebird Trans Am|actual automobile]]. Of the song, Kesha said: \"It began as a song about my car, which is a gold Trans Am, and it works about 40 per cent of the time. I don't have another car because I love that one so much. But then like all great pop it became a metaphor for something else - my pussy.\"<ref name=\"goldtransam\">{{cite web|last=Rach|first=Jessica|title=Ke$ha compares her lady-garden to her car. Thanks for that.|url=http://www.heatworld.com/Celeb-News/2013/02/Keha-compares-her-lady-garden-to-her-car-Thanks-for-that2/|work=[[Heat (magazine)|Heat]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]]|accessdate=March 22, 2013|date=February 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n\"[[C'Mon (Kesha song)|C'Mon]]\", the second single, serves as one of the album's many [[pop rap]] songs. In it, Kesha [[Rapping|raps]]: \"Saw you leaning against that old record machine/ Saw the name of your band written on the marquee/ It's a full moon tonight so we gettin' rowdy/ Yeah, we gettin' rowdy, get-get-gettin' rowdy.\"<ref name=\"mtvcmon\">{{cite web|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|title=Ke$ha Releases 'C'Mon': Listen To The 'Rowdy' Track Now!|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1697517/kesha-cmon-song.jhtml|work=MTV|publisher=Viacom|accessdate=March 22, 2013|date=November 19, 2012}}</ref> ''Billboard'' called \"C'Mon\" a [[YOLO (motto)|YOLO]] [[Dance music|dance jam]] about taking [[Casual sex|hookups]] from the dance floor to the bedroom,\" adding that the lyrics were on par with Kesha's \"[[Your Love is My Drug]]\" fecklessly juvenile attitude.<ref name=\"billboardtbt\">{{cite web|title=Ke$ha, 'Warrior': Track-By-Track Review|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/1066721/keha-warrior-track-by-track-review|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=March 22, 2013}}</ref> A [[ballad]], \"Love Into the Light\", depicts Kesha at her most vulnerable, beginning with a string of confessions and culminating in a hopeful anti-bullying anthem.<ref name=billboardtbt/> ''Billboard'' praised the song for contrasting Kesha's trademark \"glitter and [[Auto-Tune]]\" [[persona]], before highlighting \"Past Lives\" as the album's best track lyrically.<ref name=billboardtbt/> \"Last Goodbye\" tributes [[Neil Young]]'s \"[[On the Beach (Neil Young album)|For the Turnstiles]]\", while \"Only Wanna Dance With You\" received accolades for being a collaboration with members of [[The Strokes]]' music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/christopher-rosen/the-strokes-comedown-machine-kesha_b_2951705.html|title=The Strokes' 'Comedown Machine'; Or, Ke$ha Did This Better|first=Christopher|last=Rosen|date=March 26, 2013|website=Huffingtonpost.com|accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Marketing==\nThe album was tentatively due to be released in May 2012, but was later announced with an official release date of December 4, 2012. It was originally expected to be released near the end of 2011 but the delay between albums was because Kesha wanted to try to make an album that could shift the sound of pop music into a more rock direction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://calgaryherald.com/entertainment/wild+child+ride+taking+from+princess+rock+goddess/5355201/story.html|title=Ke$ha\u2019s wild child ride taking her from pop princess to rock goddess|author=Bell, Mike|date=September 5, 2011|publisher=[[Calgary Herald]]. Guy Huntingford|accessdate=April 3, 2012|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61ex8aZ7H|archivedate=September 13, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Lewis2\"/> While being interviewed by the ''[[Calgary Herald]]'' she explained the delay and elaborated on this, stating: \"I want to take enough time to make sure it's the reinvention of pop music. That's the ultimate goal, to reinvent pop music. So I'm planning on taking as much time as I need, but May sounds about right.\"<ref name=\"Lewis2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.ca/music/news/a339941/keha-my-aim-is-to-reinvent-pop-with-new-album.html|title=Ke$ha: 'My aim is to reinvent pop with new album'|author=Corner, Lewis|date=August 12, 2011|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=Hachette Filipacchi UK|accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Touring===\n{{Further|North American Tour 2013|Warrior Tour}}\n\nIn the summer of 2013, Kesha embarked on a co-headlined tour with [[Pitbull (singer)|Pitbull]]. The tour, [[North American Tour 2013]], travelled across North America, hitting venues in the United States and Canada.<ref name=\"mtvtour\">{{cite web|last=Montgomery|first=James|title=Ke$ha And Pitbull Team Up For North American Tour The unlikely duo \u2014 'Kitbull?' \u2014 announce they're hitting the road together in May.|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1704191/kesha-pitbull-tour.jhtml|work=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=April 7, 2013}}</ref> Since the joint tour did not cover any places outside of the US and Canada, Kesha decided to extend her tour and add more dates in other countries.<ref name=\"mtvwarriortour\">{{cite web|last=Depland|first=Michael|title=Ke$ha Adds 'Warrior' Tour Dates & She's Bringing Semi Precious Weapons & Mike Posner Along For The Party! Get Tickets Here!|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2013/06/20/kesha-semi-precious-weapons-mike-posner-tour/|work=MTV|publisher=Viacom|accessdate=July 27, 2013|date=June 20, 2013}}</ref> The [[Warrior Tour]] covers many places in Europe, venues throughout the US, and select places in Asia.<ref name=mtvwarriortour/> Many of the dates are parts of festivals and fairs such as [[Live at the Marquee (festival)|Live at the Marquee Festival]] in [[Cork (city)|Cork, Ireland]], the [[Wireless Festival]] in [[London|London, England]], and the [[Illinois State Fair]] in [[Springfield, Illinois]]. Before the main tour, Kesha performed many promotional tour dates throughout late 2012 and early 2013.  Those dates include stadium and TV concerts in Europe, America, Australia, and Asia in August, October, and November 2012, music festival performances in America in December 2012, more TV concerts, special music festival performances, and normal concerts in January, and February 2013 in Asia and America.\n;Promotional Tour Dates\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| Date\t  \t\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| City\t\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| Country\t\n! style=\"width:250px;\"| Venue \n|- style=\"background:#ddd;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Asia'''<ref name=\"Asia Tour Date\">{{cite web|last=Sebert|first=Kesha|title=Upcoming Events\n|url=http://www.keshasparty.com/us/event/2012/08/18/summer-sonic-2012-tokyo|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|August 18, 2012\n|[[Tokyo]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Japan]]\n|QVC Marine Field\n|-\n|August 19, 2012\n|[[Osaka]]\n|Maishima Summer Sonic Site\n|-\n|August 21, 2012\n|[[Tokyo]]\n|Studio Coast\n|- style=\"background:#ddd;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Australia'''<ref name=\"Australia Tour Date\">{{cite web|last=Lansky|first=Sam|title=\nKe$ha Performs \"Die Young\" Live On \u2018The X Factor\u2019 Australia|url=http://www.idolator.com/7252682/kesha-die-young-x-factor|work=WCPO|date=November 6, 2012|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"That Grape Juice\">{{cite web|title=Watch: Ke$ha Wakes Up \u2018Sunrise\u2019 With \u2018Die Young\u2019|url=http://thatgrapejuice.net/2012/11/watch-keha-wakes-sunrise-die-young/|work=[[Huffington Post]]|date=November 7, 2012|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|November 6, 2012\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Sydney]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Australia]]\n|UNSW Roundhouse\n|-\n|November 7, 2012\n|Seven News Centre\n|- style=\"background:#ddd;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''North America'''<ref name=\"95 Capital FM\">{{cite web|title=Ke$ha Performs New Song 'Die Young' Live On The Today Show \u2013 Video|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/kesha/news/die-young-today-show-video/|work=CAPITALFM.COM|date=November 22, 2012|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|November 17, 2012\n|[[Los Angeles]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[United States]]\n|[[Nokia Theatre L.A. Live]]\n|-\n|November 20, 2012\n|[[New York City]]\n|[[Times Square]]\n|- style=\"background:#ddd;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Europe'''\n|-\n|November 30, 2012\n|[[Stad (Sweden)|Stad]]\n|[[Sweden]]\n|Sweden XFactor Lot\n|-\n|December 1, 2012\n|[[London]]\n|[[England]]\n|London Studios\n|- style=\"background:#ddd;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''North America'''<ref name=\"North America Tour Dates2\">{{cite web|last=Fm|first=Kiss|title=\nmonday, december 3|url=http://www.kiisfm.com/go/jingleball2012/|work=Kiss Fm|date=November 12, 2012|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ke$ha Performs 'Die Young' on Conan, Tells Host About Ghost Sex in the Haunted 'Bone Zone' [Fresh Vids]|url=http://www.nashvillescene.com/nashvillecream/archives/2012/12/05/keha-performs-die-young-on-conan-tells-host-about-ghost-sex-in-the-haunted-bone-zone-fresh-vids|work=Nashville Scene|date=December 5, 2012|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=C'Mon, Ke$ha! Watch Her FEROSH X Factor Performance HERE! - |url=http://perezhilton.com/2012-12-07-kesha-c-mon-x-factor-live-results-show-performance#sthash.SDjjiRsU.xLxsiYjQ.dpbs|work=[[Perez Hilton.com]]|date=December 7, 2012|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=93.3 FLZ Jingle Ball|url=http://events.tboextra.com/tampa_fl/events/show/288267627-93-3-flz-jingle-ball-with-justin-bieber-ke-ha-onerepublic-zedd-ed-sheeran-sean-kingston-walk-the-moon-psy-austin-mahone|work=[[The Tampa Tribune]]|date=December 9, 2012|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=HOT 99.5's Jingle Ball |url=http://www.hot995.com/pages/jingleball/|work=HOT 99.5|date=December 2, 2012|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=HOT 96.1's Jingle Ball |url=http://www.power961.com/pages/landing/ke$ha_jingleball.php|work=[[HOT 96.1]]|date=December 7, 2012|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ke$ha, Sean Kingston, Others Ring In New Year 2013 'MTV's Club NYE 2013' also features performances by Rita Ora, Ne-Yo and Conor Maynard.|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1699522/kesha-ne-yo-new-years-eve-mtv.jhtml|work=MTV|date=January 1, 2013|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=iHeartRadio Celebrates CES 2013 With An Exclusive Party At Haze Nightclub Featuring A Live Performance By Ke$ha|url=http://www.zimbio.com/photos/Kesha/iHeartRadio+Celebrates+CES+2013+Exclusive/61IbD2hBHQJ|work=Zimbio|date=January 8, 2013|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=KE$HA & KILL PARIS - SUNDANCE FILM FESTIVAL - PARK CITY LIVE|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/526177617403599/|work=Facebook Events|date=January 26, 2013|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Musicians On Call |url=http://www.musiciansoncall.org/site/PageNavigator/Chapters/dc|work=On Call|date=December 14, 2012|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|December 3, 2012\n|[[Los Angeles]]\n|rowspan=\"10\"|[[United States]]\n|[[Nokia Theatre L.A. Live]]\n|-\n|December 4, 2012\n|[[Burbank, California|Burbank]]\n|Warners Brothers Studios\n|-\n|December 6, 2012\n|[[Los Angeles]]\n|The X Factor Cbs Studio 36\n|-\n|December 8, 2012\n|[[Tampa]], [[Florida]]\n|[[Tampa Bay Times Forum]]\n|-\n|December 11, 2012\n|[[Fairfax, Virginia|Fairfax]]\n|[[Patriot Center]]\n|-\n|December 12, 2012\n|[[Atlanta]]\n|[[Philips Arena]]\n|-\n|January 1, 2013\n|[[New York City]]\n|[[Times Square]]\n|-\n|January 10, 2013\n|[[Las Vegas]]\n|Haze Night Club\n|-\n|January 21, 2013\n|[[Washington DC]]\n|930 Club\n|-\n|January 26, 2013\n|[[Park City, Utah|Park City]] \n|Park City Live\n|- style=\"background:#ddd;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Asia'''\n|-\n|February 4, 2013\n|[[Tokyo]]\n||[[Japan]]\n|Harajuku Astro Hall\n|}\n\n==Singles==\n{{Listen\n|pos=right\n|filename=Ke$ha - Die Young (Audio).ogg\n|title=\"Die Young\"\n|format1=[[Ogg]]\n|description=Kesha sings over an [[acoustic guitar]] and [[Synthesizer|synthesized beat]] during this sample of the [[Synthpop|electropop]] song \"[[Die Young (Kesha song)|Die Young]]\".\n}}\nThe album's lead single, \"Die Young\" was released on September 25, 2012.<ref name=\"mtv1\">{{cite web|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|title=Ke$ha's Down-And-Dirty Party Anthem 'Die Young' Leaks|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1694367/kesha-die-young-single-leak.jhtml|work=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=October 1, 2012}}</ref> The track was soon uploaded to Kesha's BMI following the Kesha's announcement of the single, and was co-written by [[Fun (band)|Fun.]] lead singer Nate Ruess. Co-producer Benny Blanco described the track as \"old hippie rock\",<ref name=huffpost/> while Kesha described the track as \"her favourite of the album\".<ref name=\"Blanco Die Young\"/><ref name=\"Die Young BMI\"/> A 35-second music video teaser was uploaded on September 12, 2012 onto her YouTube page. A second 29-second snippet, featuring Kesha's vocals, was uploaded on September 17, 2012. The same day, Kesha published the single's artwork onto her Twitter. The song premiered and impacted US radio on September 25, 2012. It was released in Europe on November 18, 2012 and the United Kingdom on November 25, 2012, debuting in the UK at 10.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Music Releases - New Songs: October 2012|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/music-news/future-releases/|work=[[Capital (radio network)|Capital FM]]|publisher=[[Global Radio]]|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a405711/keha-whistles-new-single-die-young-on-tokyo-subway-video.html|title=Ke$ha whistles new single 'Die Young' on Tokyo subway \u2013 video|author=Corner, Lewis|accessdate=September 13, 2012|website=Digital Spy|date=September 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"C'Mon\", which was previously released as the album's first [[promotional single]], was also released as the official second single from the album.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16691 |title=Radio Industry News, Music Industry Updates, Arbitron Ratings, Music News and more! |magazine=FMQB |accessdate=December 14, 2012}}</ref> It officially impacted U.S. mainstream radio in January 2013 and peaked at 27 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100, ultimately ending Kesha's string of consecutive top 10 hits. It was further released in the United Kingdom on March 3, 2013 and peaked at number 70 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ke$ha - C'Mon - Single|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/cmon-single/id579408892|work=[[iTunes Store]]|publisher=[[Apple Inc]]|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref> The official lyric video was released on December 7, 2012.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hypable.com/2012/12/07/keha-cmon-lyric-video/| title=Ke$ha debuts \"C'Mon\" lyric video| date=December 7, 2012| accessdate=December 7, 2012| archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FfvAkSZ1?url=http://www.hypable.com/2012/12/07/keha-cmon-lyric-video/| archive-date=April 6, 2013| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n\"Crazy Kids\" was released as the third single from ''Warrior''. The song was released in a remixed form and features a guest verse by [[will.i.am]], who is listed as one of the writers on the original solo version of the song.<ref name=crazykids/> It officially impacted [[contemporary hit radio]] on April 29, 2013<ref name=\"crazykids\">{{cite web|title=Available for Airplay|url=http://fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16691|work=[[FMQB]]|accessdate=April 17, 2013}}</ref> and rhythmic/crossover radio on May 7, 2013. Crazy Kids peaked at number 40 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and Number 19 on [[Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs)|Mainstream Top 40]] becoming Kesha's least successful single at the time. Crazy Kids also charted within Australia, United Kingdom, Belgium, South Korea, Canada, and others. It was made available for purchase as a Digital download on April 30, 2013. There are also two other official remixes: One featuring rapper [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]] and one featuring rapper [[Juicy J]].<ref name=crazykids/> In May 2013, the Juicy J remix reached U.S. rhythmic airplay and became available for purchase through digital venues.<ref name=\"juicyjradio\">{{cite web|title=May 2013 radio releases|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16691|work=FMQB|publisher=Kal Rudman|accessdate=July 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 71/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|title=Reviews for Warrior by Ke$ha|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/warrior/keha |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=10 July 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/warrior-mw0002428685|title=Warrior - Ke$ha|publisher=AllMusic. [[Rovi Corporation]]|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|accessdate=December 4, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2Score = B<ref>{{cite news|last=Zaleski |first=Annie |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/keha-warrior,89338/ |title=Ke$ha: Warrior &#124; Music &#124; MusicalWork Review |newspaper=The A.V. Club |date=December 4, 2012 |accessdate=December 14, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = B<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20651688,00.html|title=Warrior - Kesha Review |author=Melissa Maerz |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=November 29, 2012 |accessdate=November 29, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4score = {{rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|author=Caroline Sullivan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/29/kesha-warrior-review|title=Kesha: Warrior \u2013 review |newspaper=The Guardian |date=November 29, 2012 |accessdate=November 29, 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Roberts |first=Randall |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-1204-kesha-review-20121204,0,427545.story |title=Kesha channels her inner 14-year-old on 'Warrior': Album review |publisher=latimes.com |date=December 3, 2012 |accessdate=December 14, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|7|10}}<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Sawdey |first=Evan |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/165932-keha-warrior/ |title=Ke$ha: Warrior |magazine=PopMatters |accessdate=December 14, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"rollingstone\">{{cite magazine|author=Rob Sheffield |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/warrior-20121204 |title=Warrior &#124; Album Reviews |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=December 4, 2012 |accessdate=December 14, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Slant Magazine]]''\n| rev8Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Slant\">{{cite web|title=Warrior - Slant review|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/kesha-warrior/2940 |author= Sal Cinquemani |date=December 3, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = 7/10<ref>{{cite web|last=Eddy |first=Chuck |url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/kesha-warrior-rca |title=Ke$ha, 'Warrior' (RCA) &#124; SPIN &#124; Albums &#124; Critical Mass |publisher=SPIN |date= |accessdate=December 14, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref name=\"USA\">{{cite news|last=Gardner |first=Elysa |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2012/12/03/listen-up-spotlight-kehas-warrior/1743983/ |title=Ke$ha is up for a fight on 'Warrior' |newspaper=USA Today |date=December 3, 2012 |accessdate=December 22, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Warrior'' received mostly positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]]. On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an average score of 71 based on 19 reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/warrior/keha/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for Warrior |website=Metacritic |accessdate=December 14, 2012}}</ref> Melissa Maerz of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave it a positive review, graded it with a (B) and said: \"Ke$ha's filthy jokes may be what separates her from her peers who practice ghost abstinence.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/> [[Drowned in Sound]] rated the album as eight-out-of-ten, called it \"a party album on a mission\" and mentioned: \"''Warrior'' is never dull, always fun, and frequently a thrillingly unpredictable ride.\"<ref name=\"dis\">{{cite magazine|last=Nellis |first= Krystina |url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/17369/reviews/4145804 |title=Ke$ha - Warrior / Releases / Releases / Drowned In Sound |magazine=Drowned in Sound |date=2012 |accessdate=December 3, 2012}}</ref> [[BBC Music]] reviewer Nick Levine, was also positive on the album and wrote: \"Taken as a whole, this is another surprisingly enjoyable album from a pop singer who has managed to broaden her approach without losing her USP.\"<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|last=Levine |first=Nick|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/mmd3|title= Ke$ha Warrior Review |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=November 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Slant Magazine]] gave a mixed review to the album, rated it as three-stars-out-of-five and said: \"Most of ''Warrior'' sticks to Ke$ha's tried-and-true formula.\"<ref name=\"Slant\"/> ''[[The Guardian]]'' reviewer went more critical on the record, blaming the artist for \"decided not to fix what ain't broke\", rated it two-stars-out-of-five and said: \"auto-Tune, deployed all over the record, turns Kesha's voice into a robo-squawk, and not in a good way.\"<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> However, Elysa Gardner of ''[[USA Today]]'' felt that the release was \"full of catchy, cannily produced tunes that promote self-indulgence as if it were a civil right, and either shrug off or embrace the risks posed by living in the moment.\"<ref name=\"USA\" />\n\nStephen Thomas Erlewine of [[Allmusic]] went deeper to the album and praised the artist for picking up the best direction for her sophomore set, gave it four-stars-out-of-five and said: \"It's a wall-to-wall party for the freaks, burnouts, outcasts, and misfits and if you don't get it that's your fault, not hers.\"<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/> ''[[New York Times]]'' reviewers were also positive on the album and linked the influences to \"drinking, sex, swearing, hard nights at the club\" and confessed that \"furtive surprise at the center of her project is sweetness, as it always was\", suggesting that she can be a country star with \"an option for her in five years or so, when she turns 30\" and described the whole record as: \"no revelation here, only strong fun.\"<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/04/arts/music/new-albums-from-kesha-and-jon-irabagon.html?_r=0|title=New Albums From Kesha and Jon Irabagon |author1=BEN RATLIFF  |author2=NATE CHINEN  |lastauthoramp=yes |date=December 3, 2012|accessdate=December 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''Warrior'' debuted at number six on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 85,000 copies in its first week.<ref name=\"billboardsales\">{{cite web|last=Lipschutz|first=Jason|title=Ke$ha Releases Statement Explaining 'Die Young' Objections|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1481289/keha-releases-statement-explaining-die-young-objections|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=March 3, 2013|date=December 20, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"warriorsales\">{{cite news|title=Ke$ha's Album Sales: Singer's 'Warrior' Gets Lapped By Month-Old Taylor Swift Album|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/12/12/kesha-album-sales-warrior-taylor-swift_n_2287442.html|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=March 3, 2013|date=December 12, 2012}}</ref> The album underwhelmed compared to her debut LP, ''[[Animal (Kesha album)|Animal]]'', which charted at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 and sold 152,000 copies in its first week of release.<ref name=warriorsales/> In December 2018, the album received a Platinum certification in the United States by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) for selling 1,000,000 copies in the country alone.<ref name=WarriorUSsales>{{cite web|last=Fekadu|first=Mesfin|title=Ke$ha Kardashian? Pop singer heads to reality land|url=http://www.denverpost.com/entertainment/ci_23095980/ke-ha-kardashian-pop-singer-heads-reality-land|work=Denver Post|date=April 24, 2013|accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref> The album debuted at number 66 on the [[UK Albums Chart]] with 2,101 copies sold. It went on to peak at number 60 in that chart, selling just 37,000 copies to date in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/ke$ha/|title=Official Charts Company|website=Officialcharts.com|accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"Die Young\", the album's lead single, was an international hit, peaking at number two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]. The single dropped down to number four, suffering massive [[airplay]] and sales cuts after the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]] caused the lyrics to be negatively interpreted by critics.<ref name=billboardsales/> Second single \"C'Mon\" debuted at number 99 on the Hot 100,<ref>{{cite web|last=Thompson|first=Erin|title=Ke$ha Sticks to Her Winning Formula with \"C'Mon\"|url=http://blogs.seattleweekly.com/reverb/2013/01/nice_hits_is_a_reverb_20.php|work=[[Seattle Weekly]]|accessdate=March 3, 2013|date=January 25, 2013|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6HNH62g8t?url=http://blogs.seattleweekly.com/reverb/2013/01/nice_hits_is_a_reverb_20.php|archive-date=June 14, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> peaking at 27<ref>{{cite web|title=Ke$ha Album & Song Chart History|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=ke$ha|chart=Hot 100}}|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 3, 2013}}</ref> effectively ending Kesha's string of top-ten hits that has accumulated since her debut single \"[[Tik Tok (song)|Tik Tok]]\".<ref name=\"bill2010\">{{cite web|last=Trust|first=Gary|title=PSY Still Stuck At No. 2 as Maroon 5 Tops Hot 100 - \"One More Night\" spends a fifth week in the top spot, while Ke$ha crashes the Top 10.|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474594/psy-still-stuck-at-no-2-as-maroon-5-tops-hot-100|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref> Crazy Kids was released as the third single off 'Warrior' and it charted in a number of countries including the United States, Australia, United Kingdom, South Korea, and others. Other charted songs include \"Thinking of You\" and the album's title track, \"Warrior\", which peaked at 14 and 25 respectively on the [[Bubbling Under Hot 100 Singles]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ke$ha Album & Song Chart History|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=ke$ha|chart=Bubbling Under Hot 100}}|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Warrior''.\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title1          = Warrior\n|note1=| length1         = 4:00\n\n| writer1         = {{flatlist|\n* [[Kesha|Kesha Sebert]]\n* [[Dr. Luke|Lukasz Gottwald]]\n* [[Max Martin]]\n* [[Pebe Sebert]]\n* [[Cirkut (record producer)|Henry Walter]]\n}}\n| extra1          = {{flatlist|\n* Dr. Luke\n* Cirkut\n* [[Emily Wright]]{{ref|a|[A]}}\n}}\n| title2          = [[Die Young (Kesha song)|Die Young]]\n|note2=| length2         = 3:32\n\n| writer2         = {{flatlist|\n* K. Sebert\n* Gottwald\n* [[Benny Blanco|Benjamin Levin]]\n*